<subsection xml:id="subsec-powers-of-10-and-common-logarithms" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Powers of 10 and common logarithms</title>
    <p>
        
    </p>
    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in Groups</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Instructions</alert>
            </p>
            <p>
                Imagine you are climbing a mountain and each step you take is a jump by a power of <m>10</m>.
                The first step is <m>10^0</m>, the second step is <m>10^1</m>, and so on.
                Each step represents a significant increase in height, just like how powers of <m>10</m> represent large numbers.
            </p>
            <p>
               1. In groups of <m>5</m>, study and fill the table below.
            </p>
            <tabular top="medium">
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Power of <m>10</m></cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Numerical Value</cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Common Logarithm</cell>
                    <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Logarithm Value</cell>

                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^0</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium">1</cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(1)</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium">0</cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^1</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(10)</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"></cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^2</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m></m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>2</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m></m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>1000</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(1000)</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"></cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^4</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10000</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m></m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>4</m></cell>
                </row>
                <row left="medium">
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^5</m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m></m></cell>
                    <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m></m></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
               2. Now, consider what happens if you take steps in the opposite direction—down the mountain—using negative powers of <m>10</m> such as <m>10^{-1}</m>, <m>10^{-2}</m>, and <m>10^{-3}</m>. 

                <ul>
                    <li>What are the numerical values of these negative powers of <m>10</m>?</li>
                    <li>What are their common logarithms?</li>
                    <li>Fill in a similar table for these negative powers of <m>10</m>.</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                3. What patterns or rules did you notice about powers of <m>10</m> and their common logarithms? Write your observations and explanations.
            </p>
            <p>
                4. Discuss your work with your classmates.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <definition xml:id="def-powers-of-10">
        <statement>
            <p>
    
                <alert>Powers of 10 </alert> are numbers that represent a base of <m>10</m> raised to an exponent.  
            </p>
             <p>
                <term>Common logarithm</term> of a number <m>x</m> is defined as the exponent to which the base <m>10</m> must be raised to obtain <m>x</m>. 
                In mathematical terms, if <m>y = \log_{10}(x)</m>, then <m>10^y = x</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <p>
        <term>Key Takeaway</term>
    </p>
    <p>
        When a number is rewritten as a power of <m>10</m>, its common logarithm is just the exponent.
    </p>
    <tabular top="medium">
        <col width="50%"/>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Number</cell>
            <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Re-written as a power</cell>
            <cell bottom="medium" right="medium">Number's logarithm</cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>1</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^0</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(1) = 0</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^1</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(10) = 1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>100</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^2</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(100) = 2</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>1000</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^3</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(1000) = 3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10000</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^4</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(10000) = 4</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>0.1</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^{-1}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(0.1) = -1</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>0.01</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^{-2}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(0.01) = -2</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>0.001</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^{-3}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(0.001) = -3</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>0.0001</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^{-4}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(0.0001) = -4</m></cell>
        </row>
        <row left="medium">
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>0.00001</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>10^{-5}</m></cell>
            <cell right="medium" bottom="medium"><m>\log_{10}(0.00001) = -5</m></cell>
        </row>
    </tabular>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               Express the following in logarithmic notation. 
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>0.00000001 = 10^{-8}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>1000000000 = 10^9</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            If <m>0.00000001 = 10^{-8}</m>. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Then, the logarithmic notation of <m>0.00000001= 10^{-8}</m> is:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{10}(0.00000001) = -8</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Since <m>1000000000 = 10^9</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Its logarithm is:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>\log_{10}(1000000000) = 9</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Determine numbers whose logarithms are equal to the following values:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="i)" cols="3">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>5</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>-3</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>8</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                To find the numbers whose logarithms are equal to the given values, we use the definition of logarithms:
            </p>
            <p>
                If <m>y = \log_{10}(x)</m>, then <m>x = 10^y</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="i)" >
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>5</m>, we have:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>x = 10^5 = 100000</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Therefore, the number whose logarithm is <m>5</m> is <m>100000</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            For <m>-3</m>, we have:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            <m>x = 10^{-3} = \frac{1}{1000} = 0.001</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Hence, the number whose logarithm is <m>-3</m> is <m>0.001</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                             For <m>8</m>, we have:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                             <m>x = 10^8 = 100000000</m>.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The number is <m>100000000</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>
   

    
</subsection>